<TEXT>
president bush on friday claimed 
progress in the war on drugs saying the days of the drug lords 
are numbered and asking tv producers to help portray the 
destructive potential of narcotics 
bush compared antidrug efforts to nations casting out 
oppressive governments saying people across america are casting 
off the oppression of drugs 
week by week day by day millions of americans in thousands 
of towns are standing up to make the same courageous choice 
drugfree neighorhoods drugfree schools drugfree kids he 
told several thousand school children at a rally sponsored by 
orange countys drug use is life abuse program 
earlier in los angeles bush urged television industry 
producers to make antidrug themes part of their programming 
he called on the academy of television arts and sciences to make 
tv a force for positive change 
at the celebritystudded santa anna rally attended by 15000 
people movie star chuck norris pledged to conquer drug traffickers 
in his next film 
the president broke the news of a massive local drug bust 
nearly a half ton of cocaine worth 30 million on the street the 
orange county sheriffs office said it would not be able to release 
details on the street but according to lt dick olson bushs 
remarks would not hurt the prosecution 
bush told the santa ana rally that the drug abuse is life 
abuse message is beginning to sink in 
recently we have seen some scattered but hopeful new signs of 
progress against the horror of drugs he said citing antidrug 
community efforts around the country 
he said cases against 14 accused international drug traffickers 
are pending in us courts following their extraditions 
the days of the drug lords may not be over yet but their days 
are numbered bush said 
bushs optimistic assessment on drugwar progress comes as his 
administration seeks 106 billion from congress to combat drugs in 
fiscal 1991 
administration officials including bushs drug policy director 
william bennett recently have been claiming there are signs of a 
turnaround in the countrys drug abuse problem 
weve covered a lot of ground in the drug war but tough 
challenges remain bush told the santa ana rally drug abuse in 
this country is still far too widespread 
continuing his lobbying for widespread community support bush 
praised the television industry for antidrug commercials and for 
programming that portrays the negative side of drugs 
thank goodness the days when popular culture glorified and 
glamorized drug use are fading fast he said 
he said he did not seek tv depiction of a fantasy world where 
drugs dont exist but rather treatment of drugs with the same 
degree of realism tv brings to so many other subjects to show 
in the real world how drugs destroy 
bush sandwiched the antidrug events into a fourday california 
trip that was primarily oriented to republican party politicking 
and a meeting with japans prime minister toshiki kaifu 
fridays rally featured appearances by los angeles rams 
cheerleaders and remarks by tv evangelist robert schuller 
the antidrug events friday followed bushs appearance at a 
california chamber of commerce dinner thursday night where he 
called on businesses to prescreen job applicants for drug use 
we need to make it very clear to every american that if you 
do drugs you dont get hired he said 
socalled casual users and their money keep these merchants of 
death in business he said 
america now condemns what has too long been condoned the 
country has had enough he declared 
