<TEXT>
a housing policy that denied an 
unmarried couple a place to live because of their relationship will 
be revised the states american civil liberties union chapter said 
thursday 
the tentative agreement with the woonsocket housing authority 
which needs the approval of us district judge ronald r lagueux 
would consider unmarried couples a family if they meet certain 
criteria including the length of the relationship whether the 
applicants have children together and the existence of joint bank 
accounts 
were going to review our policies and make some changes 
said ernest lafond the housing authoritys director who rferred 
other questions to his attorney 
the new policy stems from a lawsuit filed by susan arseneau and 
dana dagnese who sued after they were denied emergency housing in 
december 1988 following their eviction from an unsafe apartment 
a married couple in the same building was given emergency 
housing by the wha while the plaintiffs were turned down for such 
housing solely because the agency did not consider them a 
family said steve brown executive director of the aclus 
rhode island affiliate 
arseneau and dagnese had lived together for six years and were 
expecting their third child when they were evicted 
the case drew national attention when lagueux at a hearing a 
year ago at which he denied an emergency restraining order against 
enforcement of the policy said heres a couple in an illicit 
relationship who are creating children for the welfare rolls while 
others who qualify for housing are shunted aside 
brown hailed the pending agreement which affects all public 
housing as a blow to discrimination against unmarried couples 
resolution of this lawsuit will simply affirm a growing trend 
across the country in which housing authorities are recognizing 
that discrimination on the basis of marital status is unfair and 
inappropriate he said 
but the attorney for the housing authority steve rodio said 
the main reason the couple was evicted was because dagnese was 
legally married to another woman at the time 
rodio said dagneses marriage to someone else prompted lagueux 
to cite the states criminal statute against bigamy and said if 
the agency had let the couple stay in the apartment it would have 
encouraged a potentially bigamous relationship 
whether he was single or not wouldnt have mattered said 
john dineen the couples lawyer the existing rule is you have 
to be married to each other to live together 
dagnese was awaiting his divorce in massachusetts after having 
been separated for many years when he and arseneau were 
evicted said dineen 
the lawsuit filed by the aclu and rhode island legal services 
on behalf of arseneau and dagnese claimed the agencys action 
violated the couples constitutional rights to freedom of 
association family privacy and equal protection under the law 
dineen also said the policy was in violation of federal and state 
housing laws 
dineen and rodio didnt know when lagueux would rule on the 
agreement nor whether the couple still wanted to live in city 
housing 
theyre still seeking housing and they continue to want to be 
together dineen said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

