<TEXT>
an economist who favors selling off 
state enterprises and cutting the number of public employees has 
been named to brazils most powerful cabinet post 
the newly created economy ministry was created by merging the 
finance and planning ministries 
zelia cardoso de mello an advocate of freemarket reforms was 
named thursday by presidentelect fernando collor de mello the two 
are not related 
this is a sign of confidence not only in me personally but in 
a new generation said ms cardoso de mello 36 
at a news conference called to announce the appointment the 
presidentelect said this is an unprecedented challenge for the 
first time in latin american history a woman will steer the 
economic destiny of a great nation 
he said her top priority will be to fight inflation now running 
at more than 70 percent per month 
ms cardoso de mello said the new administrations economic 
program will include cuts in government subsidies selling off of a 
number of staterun companies cracking down on tax cheats and a 
tough new law to punish abusers of economic power she gave few 
details 
ms cardoso de mello said the number of ministries would be 
reduced from 23 to 12 and an undisclosed number of public 
employees would be fired 
she said brazils 114 billion foreign debt largest in the 
third world could be reduced through debtforequity swaps 
whereby creditors receive shares in publicly owned firms in 
exchange for debt 
she promised better relations with the international monetary 
fund and a renegotiation of debt payments based on new 
instruments of reducing debt service refinancing of late interest 
payments and new money 
brazil stopped paying capital on the debt in 1983 and quietly 
suspended interest payment last september to protect its 
international currency reserves 
her appointment was widely expected cardoso de mello was the 
presidentelects chief economic adviser during last years 
campaign and has headed a team preparing economic measures to be 
put into effect after he takes office march 15 
she has no previous government experience except a brief stint 
at a midlevel post in the finance ministry during the 
administration of jose sarney 
</TEXT>
