<TEXT>
an exair force pilot who admitted selling 
highlevel secrets to an fbi undercover officer posing as a soviet 
agent has pleaded guilty to espionage charges 
authorities said ronald craig wolf 34 received only a partial 
payment before his arrest in dallas he entered the plea wednesday 
to the federal charges of selling secrets in mid1989 to a 
government agent he knew by the code name sergei kitin 
us district judge sidney fitzwater has set sentencing for 
april 20 
discharged from the air force in 1981 for financial 
irresponsibility wolf had earlier pleaded innocent to the 
charges 
wolf a waco native agreed to plead guilty in exchange for a 
reduction in the severity of the charges he now faces a maximum of 
10 years in prison but could have received life imprisonment before 
the plea bargain 
the former pilot was arrested nine months ago after contacting a 
man he thought represented the soviet embassy in washington dc 
more than 15 times between march 9 and may 5 federal court records 
show wolf relayed classified documents concerning topsecret signal 
intelligence 
wolf told the purported soviet agent that he wanted to sell 
classified military documents for monetary gain and to get 
revenge for his treatment by the united states government 
according to an affidavit filed in connection with the case 
