<TEXT>
despite the nuclear regulatory commissions decision to issue a 
license to the seabrook nh nuclear plant many other reactors 
in the united states remain candidates for closure no utility has 
planned a new plant since the 1970s 
here is a list of some other troubled nuclear plants in the 
united states 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
shoreham a fully licensed plant on heavily populated long 
island about 50 miles east of new york city shoreham has never 
operated commercially the plant would be scrapped without ever 
operating under an agreement reached in may 1988 between new york 
state and the long island lighting co the bush administration 
fighting the plan wants shoreham mothballed left intact with 
radioactive material in place rather than torn down 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
three mile island cleanup operations continue on tmis damaged 
reactor more than 10 years after the nations worst commercial 
nuclear accident the undamaged sister reactor tmi unit 1 which 
was shut down during the march 1979 accident was restarted in 1985 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
shippingport the nations first commercial reactor which began 
operations in 1957 has become the worlds first commercial reactor 
to be dismantled federal officials intend to remove all 
radioactive material so the site in western pennsylvania can be 
returned to unrestricted use the reactor was sealed in concrete 
loaded aboard a barge and sent on a 8100mile journey via the ohio 
and mississippi rivers and the panama canal to a disposal site in 
hanford wash last year 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
pilgrim this massachusetts plant cited by the nrc in april 
1986 as one of the worstrun nuclear plants in the country was 
authorized to begin a gradual restart in december 1988 more than 
two years after the nrc shut the facility due to maintenance and 
management problems state officials since have asked the nrc to 
suspend the plants operating license citing inadequate evacuation 
plans and potential health problems for nearby residents 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
rancho seco voters in the sacramento calif area decided in a 
june 1988 referendum to close the longplagued rancho seco plant 
and the operating utility shut down operations a day later recent 
proposals to revive the reactor by selling the plant to another 
operator have been rejected 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
peach bottom the two peach bottom reactors in pennsylvania were 
shut down by the nrc in march 1987 after federal investigators 
found plant operators sleeping on duty a month earlier a nuclear 
industry watchdog group had called the plant a national 
embarrassment citing poor procedures and management the 
philadelphia electric co overhauled plant operations and the 
reactors went back into service in last year 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
tennessee valley authority all five of tvas operating reactors 
were shut down in 1985 for safety improvements and the first one 
back in operation sequoyah unit 2 did not restart until may 1988 
tva had to cancel plans to build eight other reactors and 
construction already under way on four others was slowed 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
palo verde licensed in 1985 palo verde was the first nuclear 
plant of what was hoped would be a standardized design that would 
speed the regulatory process but management and training 
deficiencies led to problems that have shut down the three reactors 
almost as often as they have been running the nrc has fined the 
arizona nuclear power project 810000 since 1983 for deficiencies 
in plant operations and sent a special diagnostic team last fall 
to study the facilitys problems 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
diablo canyon diablo canyon began commercial operation in 1985 
13 years behind schedule and at 17 times its originally planned 
cost design errors the discovery of the magnitude of an 
earthquake fault nearby federal licensing problems and legal 
challenges all contributed to the delay 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
turkey point the nrc has hit turkey point operated by florida 
power amp light co with about 1 million in fines over the past 
five years for safety and security violations identifying the 
plant as one of the nations 10 worst ralph naders environmental 
group public citizen has also called it one of the worstmanaged 
commercial facilities 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

