<DOCNO> AP900302-0009 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the opposition victory in nicaragua 
strips el salvadors leftist rebels of their only government ally 
in central america and tests the mettle of the regional peace 
process 
the nicaraguan conflict has absorbed most of the energy of the 
negotiations since their outset in 1987 suddenly the war is all 
but over and that leaves el salvador in the spotlight 
the full implications of the sandinista defeat remain to be 
seen but it is clearly a blow to the farabundo marti national 
liberation front 
el salvadors rightist president alfredo cristiani was elated 
by the outcome of the nicaraguan election 
the fmln is going to be left isolated like mr fidel castro 
in cuba he said of the rebel front that has been battling a 
series of usbacked governments in el salvador since 1979 
the fmln has long counted on managua for logistical and 
political support 
the salvadoran rebel front has offices in managua uses 
nicaragua for safe haven and according to us officials 
maintains a vital radio installation that serves as a command and 
control center for guerrillas in the field 
nicaragua which has the only leftist government in central 
america is also a source of arms for the fmln although the 
details are hotly debated 
the united states and the salvadoran government insist that 
nicaragua is a crucial source of weapons the sandinistas and the 
fmln dispute this 
the fmln one of the bestorganized and highly motivated rebel 
forces in the world can fight on if nicaraguas new prous 
government evicts them after taking office april 25 but the battle 
will be harder 
the loss of the only sympathetic government in the region 
clearly is serious for the fmln richard fagen the director of 
ltin american studies at stanford university and an international 
observer during the election 
some observers say the end of the nicaraguan war and the 
electoral loss of the sandinistas might pave the way for a 
negotiated solution in el salvador where a decade of war has 
claimed an estimated 73000 lives others say it might make the 
situation even more intractable 
maybe there will be a new focusing of attention a high 
priority on salvadoran peace prospects said former president 
jimmy carter another election observer 
sen christopher dodd dconn said he was afraid the 
sandinistas would pour arms into el salvador before leaving office 
on april 25 
dodd an election observer also said he feared hardliners in 
the salvadoran military and government might abandon the idea of 
negotiating assuming the sandinista loss was such a blow to the 
fmln that battlefield victory is now possible 
much depends on washington which has poured 4 billion into el 
salvador in a decade to fend off an fmln victory 
fagen said the united states will have to pressure the rightist 
government into serious talks with the fmln 
the only way to do this is to take a very active role with the 
salvadoran army he said 
the united states in central america has never been able to 
exercise its full power over local governments when it didnt have 
substantial control over the army 
one good sign for the peace process is the prospect of better 
relations between honduras and nicaragua if the 10000man 
usfinanced contra army in honduran border camps demobilizes 
if the new nicaraguan government manages to exert control over 
the sandinista army a 150000member giant armed by the soviet 
bloc regional tensions also should cool 
another strong motivation to continue the process is economic 
recovery war has sapped the regional economies and frightened away 
investors condemning millions of people to poverty 
new honduran president rafael callejas has been hoping get his 
nations staggering economy going again but like everyone elese in 
the region the fundamental condition is peace 
the prime mover of the central american peace process costa 
rican president oscar arias will be leaving office soon but a 
peaceful transition of power in nicaragua could go a long way 
towards helping the region reach the goal for which he won the 
nobel peace prize 
after the election arias said el salvador should follow 
nicaraguas example and seek a negotiated solution to the war that 
has claimed an estimated 73000 lives 
he said events in nicaragua should send a message to el 
salvador there is no sympathy in the world for those seek power 
through violence 
both the cristiani government and the fmln have said they are 
willing to talk but they are poles apart the last attempt at 
negotiations ended in midnovember when the rebels launched a 
monthlong offensive 
the fmln high command has praised the sandinistas and president 
daniel ortega for holding the election here and advancing the cause 
of democracy 
we will redouble our struggle for an authentic democracy in el 
salvador for which so much blood has been shed by our people 
the high command said after the election 
</TEXT>
