around 
perhaps the biggest compliment came from blytheville ark 
where presbyterian christian academy sixthgrader scott green 
wrote it would be neat to be in the highest court even though 
shes a girl i would still want to be sandra day oconnor 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
even a supreme court justice can slip up when offering an 
offthecuff summary of a 7yearold ruling 
oconnor recently erred in describing a freespeech decision 
stemming from demonstrations at the courts imposing building on 
capitol hill 
oconnors mistake came during oral arguments over a federal 
regulation that bans soliciting donations on postal service 
property and was sparked by justice antonin scalias questioning 
of a lawyer 
after the lawyer contended that the areas outside all post 
offices are freespeech zones scalia asked what about us would 
we have to let people demonstrate outside on court property 
in what seemed to be an effort to get back to the case at hand 
oconnor interrupted to say the court already has ruled there is 
no right to picket on court property but only on the surrounding 
public sidewalks 
well not exactly whether federal law can make the courts 
property off limits to demonstrators remains an open question 
in a case called united states vs grace the court in 1983 
unanimously struck down as unconstitutional part of a federal law 
that banned demonstrators from court property and the public 
sidewalks surrounding it 
the court said the public has a constitutional right guaranteed 
by the first amendment to use a city sidewalk as one long soapbox 
subject to reasonable time place and manner regulations 
but the decision specifically left unanswered whether the 
federal laws ban on demonstrators could be applied to the courts 
property within the city sidewalks 
we need not make that judgment at this time justice byron 
r white wrote for the court back then because the ban imposed 
by congress covers the public sidewalks as well as the building 
and grounds inside the sidewalks oconnor joined whites opinion 
the supreme court is infallible when interpreting the 
constitution because no one can secondguess it but the courts 
