<TEXT>
us and japanese negotiators face a series of 
deadlines on contentious trade issues and the rhetoric is heating 
up on both sides of the pacific as president bush meets with prime 
minister toshiki kaifu 
japanese officials are complaining of highhanded us demands 
while american officials are warning of retaliatory measures if the 
japanese do not grant concessions to reduce the huge trade 
imbalance between the two nations 
the trade dispute was expected to be at center stage when bush 
welcomed kaifu in palm springs calif this afternoon for two days 
of talks 
while no significant breakthrough was considered likely us 
officials hoped the bushkaifu discussions would at least lay the 
groundwork for progress as the negotiations proceed at a lower 
level in coming months 
there is a growing us impatience with japan especially among 
democrats in congress who point to new government figures showing 
that japan accounted for almost half of americas 1086 billion 
trade deficit last year 
the deficit with japan remained stuck at 49 billion little 
changed from a 518 billion imbalance the year before 
congress is getting tired of the games they play we cant 
crack their markets rep marty russo dill told us trade 
representative carla hills at a hearing this week 
i remain optimistic that japan will see the need to open up 
the second largest market in the world hills told reporters on 
thursday 
the japanese are upset about being singled out for americas 
trade problems many of which they believe are a product of us 
inability to compete on international markets on the campaign 
trail kaifu blasted congress for raising a sword against the 
japanese on trade issues 
hills conceded that the usjapanese relationship was at a 
difficult point and needs to have the highest level of attention 
speaking to a gathering of economists on thursday hills 
suggested that it would be extremely helpful politically for 
japan to make some trade concessions so she could point to progress 
in a report she must send congress by march 30 
the bush administration is facing a series of deadlines to 
resolve disputes over a variety of products ranging from lumber to 
super computers 
among the issues in contention 
the united states last may put japan on a trade hit list 
for its alleged unfair barriers against the sale of american wood 
products satellites and super computers the administration which 
acted under a section of the 1988 trade law known as super 301 has 
until june 16 to negotiate a removal of the barriers if the 
negotiations fail the administration can impose retaliatory 
tariffs against japanese products 
the united states and japan are engaged in an ambitious effort 
aimed at tackling the underlying causes of the trade deficit such 
as japanese exclusionary business practices and also the low us 
savings rate american negotiators have expressed disappointment 
that three rounds of discussions in the socalled structural 
impediments initiative have produced little progress an interim 
report is expected this spring and the final report is due this 
summer 
japanese barriers to the sale of american telecommunications 
products a primary source of tension between the two countries in 
recent years also are being discussed negotiators met last month 
in tokyo with the american side demanding more freedom for japanese 
companies to decide which telephone products to buy 
negotiations are going forward on other issues from 
construction to shipbuilding to protection on us patents and 
copyrights 
even as the talks continue some in congress are laying the 
groundwork to force the administration to take a tougher line 
unless the japanese grant concessions 
sen max baucus dmont has introduced legislation that would 
require retaliation if japan does not liberalize its markets for 
super computers satellites and wood products by june 16 
referring to that legislation hills said there was an urgency 
in japanese officials moving quickly before congress takes an 
action that would limit our discretion 
</TEXT>
