<TEXT>
what do hubert h humphrey everett mckinley 
dirksen mike mansfield john stennis barry goldwater claude 
pepper henry m jackson margaret chase smith sam rayburn john 
w mccormack and joe martin have in common 
the answer is not the simple one that all are retired or 
deceased members of congress 
it is rather that all are political eminences whom congress 
has chosen to honor by paying out millions of federal dollars to 
establish foundations bearing their names 
total price tag over the last 15 years more than 100 million 
the practice according to an article by julie kosterlitz in 
this weeks issue of the national journal goes far beyond merely 
naming a building for a distinguished congressional statesman 
the name of sam rayburn the late speaker of the house already 
was carved in marble on the walls of the rayburn house office 
building when in 1974 rep wright patman dtexas an old friend 
got a bright idea 
patman noted that congress was about to give 10 million in 
proceeds from the sale of the eisenhower commemorative dollar coin 
to help out financially ailing eisenhower college named for the 
late president 
patman attached an amendment requiring the college to transfer 
1 million of the eisenhower money to the sam rayburn library in 
bonham texas it was opened with private money in 1957 to house 
the papers of the speaker who died in 1961 
the bright idea soon became an established idea 
the most recent example 10 million added to a defense 
appropriations bill to endow a foundation to be named for the late 
rep claude pepper dfla and his wife mildred to carry on his 
work on behalf of the elderly 
other examples 
the 1986 barry m goldwater scholarship and excellence in 
education foundation set up to honor the retired gop senator from 
arizona by providing a recordbreaking 40 million to aid college 
students studying mathematics and the natural sciences 
the 1986 henry m jackson foundation in seattle got 10 million 
to honor the democratic senator from washington who died in 1983 
additionally the henry m jackson foundation for the advancement 
of military medicine in rockville md got 1 million to endow a 
chair in dermatology 
the hubert h humphrey institute of public affairs at the 
university of minnesota received 5 million in the late 1970s to 
honor the late democratic senator and vice president at the same 
time an institute named for the late sen everett mckinley 
dirksen rill received 25 million 
former senate majority leader mike mansfield dmont who also 
served for nearly a decade as us ambassador to japan was honored 
in 1983 by the creation of a 5 million foundation at the 
university of montana in missoula to study the nations of the 
pacific rim 
a 3 million federal grant was approved in 1982 to create a 
john w mccormack institute of public affairs at the boston campus 
of the university of massachusetts mccormack retired as speaker of 
the house in 1971 
a grant of 4 million in the late 1980s created the joseph 
martin institute for law and society at stonehill college in 
northeastern massachusetts to honor the late gop speaker of the 
house 
the john c stennis center for public service development was 
opened in starkville miss in honor of the recently retired 
democratic chairman of the senate armed services committee it 
received 75 million 
in 1989 congress approved 25 million for the margaret chase 
smith foundation which operates a library attached to the 
skowhegan maine home of the 92yearold former republican senator 
sometimes congress is asked to honor a former member and says 
no 
for various reasons it turned down requests to finance 
institutes and foundations to honor the late senate republican 
leader robert taft of ohio former house speaker thomas p tip 
oneill jr dmass and the late sen warren g magnuson dwash 
still pending is a 5 million request by maines bates college 
to house the archives of democrat edmund s muskie a former maine 
governor us senator and secretary of state 
