east german authorities have taken another 
step toward the introduction of capitalism by announcing the 
nations stateowned industries will be sold off to private 
investors starting march 15 
however land and fixed assets will not be on sale to foreigners 
in what is seen as a move to prevent a huge sellout to west germany 
also thursday the east german foreign ministry proposed that 
experts from both germanys meet soon to work out a common position 
on german unification for presentation to the world war ii allies 
the united states the soviet union britain and france 
in poland demonstrators rallied thursday in three cities to 
support their governments demand that it also be included in the 
talks poland says it needs access to the talks to win assurances a 
united germany would not claim prewar territory that is now part of 
presentday poland 
details are sketchy on the economic measures by the interim 
government of premier hans modrow which were announced by economic 
reform commissioner wolfgang krause 
the program to sell off east germanys huge industrial combines 
mainly to east german nationals begins three days before 
parliamentary elections scheduled march 18 the first free vote 
this communistled nation has seen in 40 years 
the new parliament would supervise the program and could even 
make substantial changes it could exempt some foreign investors 
from the purchasing ban if that is deemed in line with the public 
benefit krause said 
the privatization plan is a compromise between the concerns of 
west german investors who want full integration of the two 
nations economies and worries in east germany of a complete 
takeover by the west 
government spokesman wolfgang meyer said the interim step toward 
privatization would give industry managers more autonomy while 
hindering arbitrary sale of assets and property 
the lack of specifics apparently reflected the modrow 
governments reluctance to go ahead with major reforms without a 
parliamentary mandate 
modrow however also faces immense pressures to quickly restore 
confidence in his nations ailing economy as up to 3000 people a 
day continue to leave for west germany 
