and launch expeditions to mars appears reasonable but other 
strategies should also be studied the national research council 
said today 
president bush endorsed the basic elements of the plan in a 
speech last july 20 marking the 20th anniversary of the landing on 
the moon of american astronauts neil armstrong and buzz aldrin 
the proposal called for a base to be established early in the 
next century that would have a fulltime longterm staff 
the national aeronautics and space administrations strategy 
calls for frequent flights to the moon and construction there of 
living quarters laboratories and power stations the lunar soil 
would be mined to extract oxygen which then could be turned into 
rocket fuel 
bush outlined no details in his proposal and said he was leaving 
it up to nasa and to vice president dan quayle as head of the 
national space council to come up with timetables 
putting a space station in orbit has already been scheduled for 
after 1995 
nasa scientists say a moon base would be a laboratory for a 
voyage to mars bu others have questioned this saying the moon is 
not sufficiently like mars and that establishing the moon base 
would delay the mars exploration 
the national research council an arm of the congressional 
chartered national academy of sciences was asked by quayle to 
evaluate nasas strategy for the mars exploration 
david beckwith the vice presidents press secretary said 
its a very interesting report and we are pleased and grateful 
the nasa report addresses a reasonable set of technological 
and strategic approaches but not all of the technically credible 
approaches have been analyzed the council said 
it said any program for exploring the moon and mars must 
incorporate ideas from a variety of concepts some that now exist 
and others that will arise in the future 
certainly more intense scrutiny and evaluation of the options 
must take place before decisions are made regarding mission 
architecture said h guyford stever who chaired a 14member 
committee named by the council to perform the study 
this is an initial discussion to offer direction for helping 
the program get under way said stever a former presidential 
science adviser 
the committee said that although nasa does not discuss eventual 
phaseout of the space shuttle in its report on its 90day study of 
moonmars exploration the shuttle fleet will have to be replaced 
continued access of humans to space will require that planning 
begin soon for a new transportation system that will first 
supplement and then assume the shuttles role sometime between 
2000 and 2010 the committee said 
the panel disagreed with the contention of scientists at the 
lawrence livermore national laboratory that humans could be placed 
on mars by the year 2000 it said that underestimates the many 
practical and difficult engineering and operational challenges 
involved 
the nasa plan calls for placing humans on the moon in 2001 and 
on mars by 2011 at the earliest 
the research council study said even those dates depend on 
accelerating completion of the planned space station which could 
result in higher risks and costs 
in addition to replacing the space shuttle a new generation of 
launch vehicles will be needed to lift massive equipment into 
lowerearth orbit the committee said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

