a senior un official friday appealed for more 
relief funds for wartorn afghanistan and urged communist 
authorities and moslem rebels to set up noncombat zones to 
encourage refugees to return home 
sadruddin aga khan coordinator of the un economic and 
humanitarian assistance program for afghanistan said 88 million 
in cash contributions was still needed to meet this years planned 
aid target of 650 million 
he said that without additional cash contributions the united 
nations would find it difficult to make effective use of the 
material and food aid donated to afghanistan 
he said the funds were also needed to continue a program that 
already has trained 20000 afghans to detect and remove the vast 
number of unexploded antipersonnel mines that were planted during 
the countrys long conflict 
noncash assistance accounts for about 70 percent of the 
international contributions to the un program known as operation 
salam he said 
sadruddin said operation salams 1990 program would concentrate 
on agriculture food and health assistance as well as mine 
clearance 
he appealed to kabuls ruling communist government and the 
moslem rebels to reach agreement on the formal establishment of 
noncombat zones which could absorb some of the estimated 5 million 
afghan refugees who fled their country after the soviet invasion in 
1979 
sadruddin said he would discuss un plans to designate a number 
of areas as socalled zones of tranquility when he visits 
afghanistan this month 
in order to qualify as such a zone an area must be peaceful and 
local authorities must accept a un presence he said 
the un high commissioner for refugees thorvald stoltenberg 
is also due to travel to kabul with sadruddin 
despite last years soviet military withdrawal from afghanistan 
and the subsequent reduction in hostilities only about 100000 
refugees are believed to have returned home sadruddin said 
some 3 million afghans are estimated to remain in refugee camps 
in pakistan and another 2 million in iran they account for about 
40 percent of the worldwide total of refugees according to un 
figures 
the refugees have spent their 11th winter in exile we dont 
want to see them spending another year away from their country 
sadruddin said 
i am reasonably confident that with the necessary contribution 
from the international community the number of returnees this 
year could be quite substantial he added 
but he warned of a continuing exodus of afghans into iran to 
