<TEXT>
the navys inquiry into the uss iowa disaster 
failed to prove its contention that gunners mate clayton hartwig 
probably set off the explosion that killed himself and 46 other 
crewmen a congressional panel said today 
by the standards of this subcommittee and the standards that 
we think should have been applied in the navys investigation 
there is only a hypothesis and a tenuous one at that said the 
report by the house armed services investigations subcommittee 
the navy in its report on the blast concluded that hartwig 
most likely caused the explosion by inserting some type of 
detonator between bags of gunpowder in one of the ships 16inch 
guns 
navy officials did acknowledge that their evidence was 
circumstantial in light of the fact that all the witnesses 
including hartwig were killed in the blast in the battleships gun 
turret no 2 
navy spokesman cmdr mark baker asked about the panels 
criticism responded we stand by our original report 
the panel found fault with four aspects of the navys 
investigation into the april 19 1989 explosion as the battleship 
sailed near puerto rico 
rep nicholas mavroules dmass the subcommittee chairman 
said the flaws were the structure of the probe the technical 
tests police work and psychological analysis 
first the navy convened a oneman investigation without the 
use of formal hearings mavroules said in a statement 
accompanying the report if the navy had convened a board of 
several members operating through formal hearings the theories and 
hypotheses that evolved would have faced more rigorous questioning 
instead there was an excess of certitude he said 
on the technical inquiry mavroules said that when navy 
investigators were told that hartwig owned a timing device the 
tests proved that a timer was used to trigger the blast 
later he said when the timer information proved to be false 
the technical tests suddenly found a chemical detonator to be the 
logical igniter 
