<TEXT>
east germanys army has suffered a loss of 
morale readiness and nearly a quarter of its troops since the 
borders were opened and the perception of a threat from the west 
began to diminish 
east german troops have deserted sold their uniforms in the 
west and some even refused to take part in a military exercise last 
month with soviet troops 
defense minister theodor hoffmann has conceded that reform has 
inflicted many difficulties on the oncefeared frontline force 
of the warsaw pact 
we are practically without subordinates a senior army 
officer said the officers themselves have to walk patrols and 
service tanks 
the officer who spoke on condition he not be identified said 
the army has been hit hard by the departure of thousands of 
soldiers through the open borders with the west 
col gerd aperz of the defense ministry information office said 
reports of the east german armys diminished defense capability 
have been exaggerated in the west but confirmed the emigration to 
west germany has taken its toll on the force 
he also noted that more than 10 percent of the national peoples 
army troops are deployed in factories municipal maintenance crews 
and in other public works to keep crucial industries and services 
operating despite the daily departure of thousands of workers 
more than 40000 soldiers have left army service since jan 26 
when a military reform was announced to cut what was then a 
200000troop force to 110000 by the end of the year aperz said 
but other defense ministry sources said only about half of the 
departures were due to the planned reduction that was to be phased 
in over the year 
increasing numbers have deserted to seek their fortunes in the 
west or failed to report back from furloughs amid a noticeable 
decline in discipline and readiness the sources said 
capt olaf marks said nearly half of the 2000 soldiers 
stationed at his 23rd rifle regiment based in bad salzungen had 
left in recent weeks 
they join more than 400000 east germans who have fled to west 
germany since last summer having abandoned hope that their living 
standards will improve 
reform is being blamed for much of the decline in what was once 
viewed as the strongest fighting force in eastern europe and the 
most strategically located due to its border with nato member west 
germany 
improved relations between the two germanys as well as between 
the two military alliances to which they belong have changed 
perceptions of westerners from enemies to friends and greatly 
reduced east german fears of a military threat emanating from 
across the border 
a young officer at this weeks session of political talks 
between communists and opposition parties said many east german 
soldiers can no longer conceive of circumstances that would prompt 
them to take up arms against their west german brothers 
hoffmann the defense minister also addressed the session 
appealing to politicians not to make the army a campaign instrument 
in the march 18 balloting east germanys first free elections 
expectations of imminent unification of the two germanys has 
encouraged the east german force to seek means of cooperating with 
the west german bundeswehr rather than planning for counterattacks 
that seem increasingly unlikely to be needed 
military strategists from east germany and west germany have 
been discussing ways of sharing defense burdens in the event the 
nations are unified 
a joint east germansoviet exercise near berlin in early 
february had to be scaled back after some east german troops 
refused to take part 
aperz confirmed some soldiers objected because they considered 
the exercise to be in conflict with the new reform character of 
the army but denied reports the soldiers refused to work with the 
soviet troops 
east germany is host for the bulk of the soviet unions 565000 
troops deployed in eastern europe which has long been a matter of 
resentment among residents of the regions where the soviets are 
stationed 
the kremlin has not yet faced significant pressure from east 
germans to pull out its troops but a large withdrawal is expected 
to be negotiated soon at the viennabased negotiations on 
conventional armed forces 
in the meantime signs abound that the army has been taking its 
responsibilities less seriously 
in search of hard currency to buy consumer goods during western 
visits some soldiers sell their uniform jackets hats and ensignia 
at the thriving west berlin flea market near the checkpoint charlie 
border crossing 
on a recent afternoon one brownclad soldier approaching a 
ditchdigging brigade drew a crowd of impressed fellow soldiers 
around him when he displayed what two passing american reporters 
mistook for a grenade launcher 
its a muffler the soldier corrected the foreigners as his 
fellow troops broke into howls of laughter i just bought it over 
in west berlin 
