<DOCNO> AP900302-0158 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the nations largest banking trade group on 
friday endorsed a plan to reform deposit insurance and force 
uninsured depositors to accept some losses in bank failures 
the american bankers associations plan would continue 100000 
per account coverage but it would eliminate the current de facto 
practice of treating some banks as too big to fail 
accounts over the 100000 limit would be subject to an 
immediate haircut based on the federal deposit insurance 
corps experience with past bank failures 
the haircut would change probably once a year but if the plan 
were in effect now uninsured depositors would probably lose 12 
cents on every dollar the trade group estimates 
currently depositors are guaranteed nothing beyond 100000 
but in practice regulators have guaranteed all deposits at large 
institutions because theyre afraid a collapse of a major bank 
would ripple through the financial system causing runs on banks 
generally 
as a matter of fairness regulators also usually protect all 
deposits when a small institution fails 
the american bankers proposal is similar to one advanced last 
summer by former federal deposit insurance corp chairman william 
issac now a private banking consultant 
the idea is to encourage safe banking by giving large depositors 
an incentive to put their money only into sound institutions 
reform proponents attribute at least part of the savings and loan 
crisis to the fact that depositors had little reason to care 
whether theyre institution was well or poorly run 
robert dugger chief economist of the banking group argued that 
the reform proposal would prevent banks and sampls from embarking on 
fastgrowth risky investment strategies the deposits wouldnt be 
available to do that 
also regulators because of the threat of deposit withdrawals 
would be forced to step in immediately when a bank fails 
minimizing the losses he said 
however others warn that tinkering with deposit insurance 
coverage could destabilize the financial system leaving it 
vulnerable to lightningquick runs 
the signal would pass that funds over 100000 are at risk i 
think that signal is potentially dangerous not only for little 
banks but for big banks said kenneth guenther executive vice 
president of a rival trade group representing smaller banks the 
independent bankers association of america 
the american bankers proposal approved by the groups board of 
directors and a 400member leadership conference is being 
forwarded to the treasury department which is studying deposit 
insurance 
treasurys recommendations due next february are expected to 
form the basis of major banking legislation in 1991 
deposit insurance was enacted in 1934 as part of the financial 
reforms put in place after the 1929 stock market crash and the wave 
of bank failures in the early 1930s 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

