the us army is seeking repayment of a 25000 
scholarship from a student who says he is homosexual 
james holobaugh 24 won a full fouryear rotc scholarship to 
attend washington university in st louis and was featured in a 
nationwide recruiting campaign he was scheduled to be commissioned 
an army officer last may through the reserve officer training 
corps but after his acknowledgement the military moved to refuse 
his commission 
under a department of defense policy homosexuals are considered 
unsuitable for military service and are not permitted to serve the 
policy says their presence in the military would seriously impair 
discipline good order morale and security 
william b rubenstein a staff counsel for the lesbian and gay 
rights project of the american civil liberties union and 
holobaughs attorney said thursday it was not unusual for 
homosexual cadets to be removed from the rotc but he said this was 
the first case the aclu knew of where the army had asked for its 
scholarship money back 
at an informal hearing in december the army questioned whether 
holobaugh was masquerading as a homosexual to evade his service 
obligation rubenstein said after completing the rotc program 
students commissioned as officers must serve in the military for 
four years of active duty or eight years in reserves 
in january the army ruled that no evidence existed that 
holobaugh was trying to evade service rubenstein said 
nonetheless the army recommended against commissioning holobaugh 
and in favor of forcing him to reimburse the military for his 
scholarship 
the case is being reviewed by the commander of the us army 
second region at fort knox ky 
holobaugh was rated one of the top performers in his rotc class 
at washington university and was selected by the army to be in a 
nationwide advertising campaign to attract students 
it wasnt until late 1988 or early 1989 that he realized he was 
homosexual holobaugh said last april he sought the advice of a 
rotc captain who told him to tell the army he was homosexual then 
rather than wait until after his commission 
holobaugh said he was appalled at the prejudice in the 
military against homosexuals its kind of blowing my mind he 
said 
he said he wanted to be an army officer if he cannot be 
commissioned in the army he said i will without a doubt fight 
to not have to pay back my scholarship 
