<TEXT>
outraged highland peasants armed with 
sickles and homemade shotguns captured 13 shining path guerrillas 
killed them and sent their heads to the local army commander 
police said friday 
police said 200 peasants who organized into a village defense 
group because of their fears of reprisals by the maoistinspired 
insurgents ambushed 20 shining path rebels thursday near cochas a 
town 30 miles northeast of huancayo 
using machetes sickles lances and homemade shotguns the 
peasants overpowered the betterarmed but outnumbered guerrillas 
capturing and decapitating nine of them 
the incident occurred three days after peasants from the 
neighboring village of comas captured four shining path guerrillas 
including one woman and cut off their heads 
police in huancayo 120 miles east of lima said the peasants 
put the heads into bags and sent them to the provincial army 
commander in concepcion 12 miles northwest of huancayo they also 
sent weapons and propaganda confiscated from the rebels 
military officials in concepcion would not comment 
the civil defense groups called rondas are organized by 
the army to defend remote villages from guerrilla incursions often 
the peasants are armed only with crude weapons and are no match for 
the guerrillas many of whom carry automatic weapons and explosives 
many of the peasant groups complain they receive little support 
from the army confrontations between the rondas and rebels have 
become more frequent in recent months and dozens have been killed 
on both sides 
the shining path says it wants to create a workerpeasant state 
patterned on the ideas of mao tsetung but in its 10 years of 
armed struggle it has not gained wide support among perus peasants 
police said the villagers in comas and cochas complained the 
rebels had been harassing them stealing their food and ordering 
them to stop shipping farm produce to the cities 
part of the rebels announced strategy is to choke off food 
shipments from the huancayo region perus breadbasket to the 
population centers on the coast mainly the capital city of lima 
and its port callao 
the shining path guerrillas began fighting to overthrow perus 
elected governments in 1980 launching its first attack in the 
southern andes highlands 
the rebels now operate through most of the andes and the 
cocaproducing jungles of the northeast where drug traffickers pay 
them for permission to operate 
the guerrillas also occasionally launch attacks in lima and 
other cities along the coast where the majority of peruvians live 
conducting hitandrun assaults and dynamiting electrical 
substations 
the government says more than 18000 people have died in the 
decade of violence most of them unarmed civilians 
