marine animals and blackened hundreds of miles of rocky shoreline 
the prosecution memo suggested that hazelwoods intent would be 
a key issue in the jurys deliberations 
the state agrees that it was not captain hazelwoods intent to 
damage property of another when he tried to remove the vessel 
said the document however at the time he was attempting to 
remove the vessel he had sufficient information to know that such 
action would risk damaging property of another 
to be found guilty of second degree criminal mischief the 
felony the jury must determine that hazelwood recklessly risked 
the property of another in an amount exceeding 100000 
