<TEXT>
american business leaders said friday they 
expected no major breakthrough on contentious trade issues in the 
weekend talks between president bush and japanese prime minister 
toshiki kaifu 
however they held out hope that the discussions could set the 
stage for a fullfledged trade summit between the two leaders later 
in the year 
the hastily arranged two days of talks between bush and kaifu in 
palm springs calif were being viewed by many industry officials 
as a promising development for separate trade talks which had 
bogged down in recent weeks 
the talks known as the structural impediments initiative aimed 
to attack the underlying causes of the huge 49 billion trade 
imbalance between america and japan by dealing with such areas as 
japans exclusionary business practices and americas low savings 
rate 
however the discussions so far have produced no movement and 
american negotiators were openly pessimistic about the chances of 
success following the conclusion of the third round of talks last 
week in tokyo 
economists of all persuasions and the bush administation agree 
that even if japan eliminated all restrictive practices about which 
the united states has complained most of the 49 billion imbalance 
would remain because of the american appetite for japanese cars 
electronic equipment and other goods 
jerry jasinowski president of the national association of 
manufacturers the largest trade group for us manufacturing 
companies said bush deserved a lot of credit for trying to get the 
stalled discussions back on track 
bush has put his prestige on the line to emphasize the 
importance of these talks jasinowski said we were dead in the 
water and this is an opportunity to breathe some life back into the 
effort 
jasinowski said that while the meeting between bush and kaifu 
was not expected to resolve any of the major issues between the two 
countries it would serve to highlight the importance both leaders 
saw in making progress 
he said kaifu may offer at the session to appoint a highlevel 
official of his government to oversee the discussions in japan and 
to coordinate responses in the massive japanese bureaucracy 
he said another possible outcome was agreement by both bush and 
kaifu to meet again in the fall for a longer session examining the 
whole range of trade disputes between the two countries 
separately from the summit in addition to the review of 
underlying trade barriers there are talks about specific products 
which the bush administration has charged are being unfairly 
restricted these talks cover american lumber products 
supercomputers and satellites 
john swenson a spokesman for cray research inc the leading 
manufacturer of supercomputers said his company had heard of no 
breakthrough in the discussion on supercomputers 
a congressional source who spoke on condition that his name not 
be used said that kaifu was expected to announce on saturday lower 
tariffs on a portion of us finished wood products although the 
reduction would cover only a small portion of us lumber sales to 
japan 
william archey top trade expert at the us chamber of 
commerce said that kaifu would be following the pattern of past 
japanese leaders if he offered small concessions in trade 
the historical approach of other japanese heads of government 
has been to offer these limited morsels we then get excited 
because they threw us a nibble he said 
pressure is growing in congress to see results in the japanese 
discussions 
senate finance committee chairman lloyd bentsen dtexas in a 
letter to bush last week urged the president to press kaifu 
with all the formidable persuasion at your command to open the 
japanese market 
sen max baucus dmont and the chairman of a senate trade 
subcommittee prepared legislation that would force the 
administration to retaliate if there has been no progress by the 
june 16 deadline in the talks covering wood supercomputers and 
satellites 
baucus scheduled a hearing of his subcommittee for monday at 
which time various administration witnesses were scheduled to 
appear to report on the developments in the discussion to date 
