any difference but youve got to try 
people around here say they dont regard themselves as the 
protesting kind they live quietly in old coastal towns where 
boarded up ice cream stands are part of the offseason charm 
no one much wants to get arrested or stand with picket signs in 
the shadow of seabrook which is perched on a bluff over one of 
several popular summertime beaches 
but many citizens have joined the clamshell alliance and have 
been united since the early 1970s behind an antinuclear banner 
they say the government hasnt established an effective evacuation 
plan and fear there would be chaos on the narrow streets out of 
town if a nuclear emergency occurred 
seabrook has been the acid test for the national agenda for 
nuclear power said james dougherty a vocal newburyport realtor 
and father of two we are the caretakers of our own safety 
we have to keep driving the issue 
seabrook was proposed in 1972 as a twinreactor plant costing 
less than 1 billion construction delays and cost increases forced 
the cancellation of one reactor in the mid1980s and plunged lead 
owner public service co of new hampshire into bankruptcy 
reorganization in 1988 
the plant became a symbol of the antinuclear movement and its 
foes claimed a broader victory contending that no utility would 
now risk the costs of trying to build and open another nuclear 
plant 
