<TEXT>
here is a look at greyhound lines inc the dallasbased company 
that operates the only nationwide bus system the companys 6300 
drivers are on strike principally over wage issues 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
greyhound lines inc is the descendant of a bus operation that 
began in 1914 when swedish immigrant carl eric wickman established 
the jitney line in hibbing minn charging 25 cents for a round 
trip on the companys lone hubmobile between hibbing and the alice 
saloon 
the current company was formed in 1987 through a leveraged 
buyout of the bus operations of phoenixbased greyhound corp fred 
g currey a career bus executive led an investment group that 
paid 270 million for greyhound four months later curreys gli 
holding inc bought trailways lines inc of dallas for 80 million 
and merged the two bus lines 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
most of the companys 11825 employees are represented by the 
striking amalgamated council of greyhound local unions the union 
has all 6300 drivers plus 1660 office workers and 1475 
maintenance workers there are another 690 maintenance employees 
represented by the international association of machinists who 
agreed to a fouryear contract last fall the united auto workers 
also represents employees at the companys eagle bus manufacturing 
inc in brownsville texas there are 1700 employees not subject 
to collective bargaining 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the main issue revolves around pay before curreys group bought 
the company in 1987 the union agreed to a 22 percent wage cut 
although the company says its drivers are the highest paid in the 
industry except for some small regional companies in the northeast 
the company says drivers averaged 24743 in 1989 a 1080 
increase over 1987 the 1500 highest paid averaged 33218 and its 
highest paid driver made 48800 
greyhound says its offer would give drivers a 141 million or 
69 percent raise in the first year and 135 percent over the life 
of the 3year contract 
the union says those figures are misleading because of the 
inclusion of incentive bonuses the union claims its offer would 
cost 17 million in the first year and 15 million each of the next 
two years the company however says the unions offer would cost 
more than 200 million 
other issues involve pension plan contributions and regional 
pay rates for mechanics 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
greyhound operates three businesses intercity passenger 
service charter service and small package delivery its 3938 
buses serve about 9500 locations and are the only public 
intercity transportation in about 9000 of those areas 
the company says it has improved each year since the buyout 
with revenue passenger miles the most meaningful traffic measure 
rising from 609 billion in the year before the buyout to 748 
billion last year in all about 22 million passengers traveled an 
average of 335 miles each on greyhound last year 
the company says its traffic has grown faster than other modes 
of transportation up 98 percent last year versus 43 percent for 
cars 42 percent for amtrak and a 01 percent loss for airlines 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
after losing 20 million in its first two year greyhound 
expects a 730000 profit for 1989 on 1 billion in revenue 
the company has about 340 million in longterm debt but no 
significant principal payment due until 1992 greyhound plans to 
spend 103 million over the next three years to upgrade equipment 
and terminal operations capital expenditures have totaled 183 
million in the last three years 
