he was unwilling to predict any time frame for negotiations or the 
return of exiles 
we are already making progress there is no reason why we 
should not be able to make further progress he said i am 
optimistic that the process of removing all obstacles to 
negotiations is on i will be surprised if we dont succeed in 
removing the obostacles 
the anc is demanding the lifting of the state of emergency and 
the release of all political prisoners as preconditions to talks 
aimed at ending the apartheid system that denies south africas 28 
million blacks a vote in national life 
on feb 16 the anc said it was prepared to send a delegation to 
south africa for talks with de klerk on how to proceed 
mandela said the anc welcomed wideranging reforms so far by de 
klerk but the anc sought only to negotiate on an equal footing with 
the ruling national party 
as long as political prisoners are not released and the state 
is emergency is not lifted in its entirety we are not on equal 
terms he said 
of his own release mandela said the release of one prisoner 
when there are 3000 others cant be such an important 
development 
the veteran black leader said the national executive would in 
due course announce the names of delegates it wants to travel to 
cape town for the preliminary talks with de klerk 
south africa says it wants the anc to abandon its commitment to 
guerrilla hostilities and there have been calls from south african 
church leaders and president kenneth kaunda of zambia for 
guerrillas to suspend their operations inside south africa 
if the government gives us the opportunity we will move away 
from confrontation but it is up to the government to decide 
mandela said 
the anc has waged a bombing and sabotage campaign since 1961 but 
there have been few attacks recently and the guerrillas have had 
little military impact 
by his election as the ancs no 2 mandela effectively becomes 
the organizations top leader 
tambo suffered a stroke in august and is widely believed unable 
