<TEXT>
a third of the senate appealed to the leaders 
of east and west germany on friday to merge their countries 
existing border treaties with poland in order to allay polish fears 
the bipartisan group of 34 senators called on west german 
chancellor helmut kohl and east german prime minister hans modrow 
to come up with a single treaty that would bind a unified germany 
to honor the present border with poland along the oder and western 
neisse rivers 
the joint treaty would be initialed by the two leaders now but 
would only be ratified by a united german parliament once 
unification is achieved the senators proposed 
we believe as you do that inviolability of the postwar 
european borders is a cornerstone for world peace and 
stability the senators wrote the move was initiated by 
senator paul simon dill a member of the foreign relations 
committee 
any remaining ambiguity about german intentions concerning the 
present german borders with poland should be eliminated as soon as 
possible the senators said 
as steps toward uniting east and west gather momentum poland 
has become increasingly nervous that the territory it was given 
after world war ii comprising onethird of presentday poland 
might be claimed by a united germany 
kohl has dismissed such fears as groundless and said this week 
that he would favor the two german parliaments making formal 
statements that recognize polands western border 
but despite repeated pressure from opposition parties at home 
and from foreign leaders he has refused to commit himself to a 
binding position on the subject saying only a unified german 
government and parliament could make such a pledge some analysts 
have seen his reluctance as motivated by a desire to avoid giving 
an issue to the very small extreme nationalist groups in west 
germany 
each germany has a separate treaty with poland defining their 
borders 
in their cable to the two leaders the senators said a unified 
treaty would put to rest legitimate concerns of poland and would 
facilitate the process leading to german unification 
it also would respond to chancellors kohls concern that the 
present treaty between poland and the federal republic of germany 
could not be legally binding on a united germany the cable said 
