<TEXT>
the latest edition of crisis is a firstclass 
comic book readable graphic and vibrant but it deals in human 
rights not jokes or superheroes 
the twicemonthly publication with a print run of up to 40000 
was launched a year ago and has become one of britains most 
popular comic books telling stories of animal rights the 
environment and racism 
for its latest issue crisis joined forces with amnesty 
international the human rights organization based in london to 
bring youngsters the grim reality of such as the upington 14 in 
south africa 
we are going after a new younger audience said dan jones 
head of campaigns at amnesty part of our problem is that amnesty 
international produces the most extraordinary stories and then 
they are put into an inaccessible form 
most previous stories in crisis were fictional but the amnesty 
international edition is presented as straight fact 
the comic book tells the story clearly and dramatically 
without lowering amnesty internationals high standards for facts 
and details jones said our name is on the paper and our 
reputation goes with it 
lifelike color drawings tell the story of the upington 14 
and their confinement on death row in pretoria prison 
fourteen blacks were sentenced to death for the mob killing of a 
black policeman in upington northwestern south africa in november 
1985 they were not proved guilty as individuals but were 
sentenced under a doctrine called common purpose which held 
them responsible as part of the mob 
on the last page of the story are statistics of executions in 
south africa and a statement that says 
amnesty international is opposed to the death penalty in 
the case of south africa it asks that a judicial enquiry be 
appointed to look into the use of the common purpose doctrine 
jones said a paragraph was added at the last minute to inform 
readers that president fw de klerk of south africa suspended the 
death penalty feb 2 
pat mills a senior crisis scriptwriter and artist sean 
phillips prepared the edition using amnesty files 
when amnesty international came along with specific cases i 
realized i didnt have to hide behind fiction mills said i 
could come straight out with it because it is based on real life 
not made up in any way and it blows away any movie 
the second story in the amnesty issue is about the humiliation 
and suffering of young palestinians engaged in the uprising against 
israeli rule in the west bank and gaza strip 
amnesty international has recorded a wide range of severe 
violations of human rights by the israeli security forces says 
the message at the end over 540 palestinians have been shot dead 
