<TEXT>
the whistling winds off the atlantic 
once carried sailing ships to this tiny island and the welcoming 
sight of the sankaty lighthouse 
now those winds are ripping away the sand and soil that anchor 
the beacon and soon its light like the whalers will be gone 
but sankaty may have a savior in a 75yearold painter named 
robert perrin the pinkcheeked silverhaired maverick who has 
made the island his home has painted the lighthouse and is 
donating 20 percent of the proceeds from the sale of each 150 
print to an effort to save the lighthouse 
his fund raising may amount to little more than a drop in an 
ocean but to perrin it doesnt matter his time as a painter is 
running short glaucoma has claimed most of the sight in his right 
eye and weakened blood vessels in his left may steal what sight 
remains 
with his fading vision he has seen many nantucket landmarks 
torn down to make way for developers wanting to open up the island 
for more summer visitors and tourists sankatys light he said 
wont be extinguished 
everyone says it cant be done perrin said of his efforts 
to save the lighthouse but im a stubborn cuss 
the odds against him are daunting the 140yearold lighthouse 
must be moved back from its eroding 110foot bluff or be swept out 
to sea in the next decade a us army corps of engineers study 
estimated it will cost 840000 to move sankaty 
so two years ago perrin painted a majestic seascape of the 
beacon rising over the stormy atlantic 
the undertaking was no piece of cake perrin wanted the work to 
be a view from the sea but after clambering down the bluff to the 
beach easel and brushes in hand he realized the lighthouse wasnt 
visible from that vantage point visiting seabirds didnt make the 
task any easier 
i got divebombed by terns when i was walking along the 
beach perrin recalled then i couldnt see anything when i got 
there boy was i mad 
the painting in the end had to be created from the artists 
imagination so far sales have been slow but perrin also plans to 
lobby sen edward kennedy dmass who secured 12 million in 
federal money to reconstruct nantuckets great point lighthouse 
which washed into the sea in a storm in 1984 
sankaty is one of a handful of the 139 new england lighthouses 
run by the us coast guard that will fall into the sea in the next 
decade if steps arent taken to save them according to coast guard 
lt paul reid in boston 
reid said despite modern navigation systems lighthouses still 
help ships at sea find their way to shore 
lighthouses are major aids to navigation theyre on all 
navigational charts reid said and even in the biggest ships 
electronics can always go on the fritz sailors like to have the 
lighthouses there something thats always dependable 
pottering around his gallery scattered with easels canvasses 
yellowing photographs and artifacts from the island perrin jokes 
about his fading sight and his work 
i could be a great abstractionist with my right eye or i 
could turn to sculpture of course id have to do it by feel and 
it would have to be with female models said perrin still a 
bachelor 
his nantucket paintings many filled with halfvisible 
ghostlike images of people and landmarks long gone provide a sort 
of visual history of the old nantucket 
you can go anywhere and see brandnew buildings brandnew 
this brandnew that perrin said but old places and things 
have their own character 
like he hastens to add the sankaty lighthouse 
i could say to heck with it and not take my medication and 
maybe id be blind in a few years perrin said but the 
lighthouse is still there lets save it before something happens 
