<TEXT>
residents of the nations snowiest town 
are proud of how theyve shoveled burrowed and bulldozed through 
this winters record snowfall of more than 40 feet 
but after more than three months of steady snow even the most 
devoted fans of winter start pining for that distant rumor called 
spring 
i dont think its ever going to melt airplane scheduler 
nettie pike said recently while waiting out yet another storm at 
the valdez airport this is the new ice age 
streets have become trenches walled in by 10foot snowbanks so 
enduring that kids paint graffiti on them drifts reach halfway up 
secondfloor windows and six snowheavy boats have capsized in the 
harbor 
valdez crowded onto a narrow plain by prince william sound 
forms an ideal catch basin for the oceanspawned snow storms that 
stall against the steepwalled chugach mountains behind town 
at last official count snow on the ground measured 105 inches 
though depths vary throughout town in the lee of hills the 
branches of buried trees claw up through snowdrifts downtown 
bulldozers push icy boulders a ton at a time into mountains 45 feet 
high 
residents dont let it keep them from their business interrupt 
their shoveling for a moment and most will say a bit defensively 
that they dont mind the snow 
at least its not cold gene mcdaniel said as he tried to 
start his snowblower at 20 degrees over the mountains in the 
interior it really gets cold id much rather have this snow than 
45 below 
thats not to say there arent inconveniences 
mcdaniel figured it was time to shovel his roof one night when a 
mass of snow sloughed off blocking his front door and trapping him 
and his guests his snowclearing bill this season stands at 700 
workers at the state department of environmental conservation 
office ran out of room while plowing the parking lot so they 
started pushing snow up onto a nearby pile an angry neighbor soon 
arrived shouting youre putting your snow on my pile take it 
off 
ed nielsen maintenance man at the village inn motel said hes 
been shoveling steadily for a month tunneling down to fire exits 
and fighting a losing battle to keep drifts from walling up the 
windows 
it feels like youre in a dungeon neilsen said people 
start getting itchy feet and getting cranky at each other 
people are kind of schizophrenic said bob donald director 
of the valdez national health center in the summer everyones 
busy as a bee in the winter a lot of people sleep longer they 
come home from work eat watch some tv and are in bed by 9 
oclock and they still feel like theyre not getting enough rest 
its kind of a selfimposed hibernation 
attendance is up at the public library where travel books about 
hawaii are popular 
last fall many valdez residents were looking forward to the 
slower pace winter brings the towns population of 3000 more than 
doubled last summer after the exxon valdez oil spill the largest 
in us history but when exxon suspended its cleanup sept 15 the 
crowds thinned and valdez was left to face its snow alone 
the first measureable snow fell oct 23 by the end of december 
it was halfway up firstfloor windows januarys snowfall of 158 
inches broke the local onemonth record and on feb 13 when 
snowfall topped 3847 inches it erased the modernday seasonal 
record set in 1987 the national weather service didnt start 
recording the towns snowfalls until 1972 
last week another storm pushed the snowfall toward the 500inch 
mark said weather service spokesman lynn chrystal 
chrystal who doubles as valdez mayor concedes the towns 
snows dont match nearby thompson pass considered alaskas 
snowiest spot nor does valdez compare to paradise ranger station 
at mount rainier wash which set the nations seasonal snowfall 
record with 935 feet in the winter of 197172 
but those are isolated outposts chrystal said valdez with an 
annual average snowfall of about 25 feet qualifies as the nations 
snowiest town he said 
for now many residents hide in taverns like the pipeline club 
where they can play a round of darts a wintertime obsession here 
or hear louie the bartender brag for the hundredth time about the 
halibut he caught last spring 
ah yes spring when cars lost for the winter rise out of 
melting snowbanks and the mountains turn from white to brown to 
green 
chrystals forecast both as weatherman and mayor theres 
optimism in the air we know that winter is not too much longer 
it stops snowing by may and most on the ground melts by june 
though patches persist well into july chrystal said while that 
may seem a chilly springtime its the sweetest time of year to the 
snowweary people of valdez 
theres something about april chrystal said dreamily the 
sky is the bluest of any time of year its just breathtaking i 
cant wait until the ice melts off my boat 
</TEXT>
