<TEXT>
silviu brucan put it in writing more 
than two years ago by 1990 a new generation would be leading 
eastern europe 
as he watched the dominoes tumble last year however the 
stalinistturneddissident feared he had been wrong about his own 
country 
when december came i got frightened that i have only one 
month and when dec 22 came i was relieved he said with a broad 
smile we did it 
brucan 74 is the eminence grise of the national salvation 
front which took over when communist dictator nicolae ceausescu 
was overthrown dec 22 and executed dec 25 
he has resigned from its leadership but remains in his large 
office giving advice and planning the fronts campaign for the may 
20 election 
two months after a popular uprising ended ceausescus 24year 
reign the revolution in little romania is having an impact on the 
two communist giants the soviet union and china brucan said 
millions of chinese whose prodemocracy uprising was crushed by 
the army in june are fixated on the success of romanian uprising 
which the army supported he said in an interview 
its a romanian obsession in china and that will topple the 
communists he said and not only in china i think it affected 
perhaps even more so the soviet union 
before decembers events in romania he said the decisions of 
the soviet communist partys central committee including 
relinquishing its monopoly on power were inconceivable 
brucan has been a journalist academic and ambassador to the 
united states in 19561959 and the united nations in 19591962 
once a stalinist and ranking communist party member he broke with 
ceausescu in 1965 
ceausescu put him under house arrest in march 1989 along with 
five others who signed an open letter criticizing the dictator 
his reemergence in revolutionary romania has been 
controversial brucan has been denounced both as a stalinist and as 
an advocate of the economic policies of mikhail gorbachev 
by his own definition brucan rejected stalinism long ago and is 
committed to multiparty democracy 
communist parties in eastern europe are doomed to extinction 
by a scientific and technological revolution that created distinct 
social groups and virtually destroyed the working class that was 
their base of support he said 
in an article published in september 1987 by the boston monthly 
worldpaper and reprinted in the international herald tribune he 
foresaw the collapse of the soviet bloc dictatorships 
conservative leaders clinging to economic orthodoxy face a 
formidable challenge that is bound to accelerate the changing of 
the guard he wrote by 1990 a new political generation will be 
in command all over eastern europe 
brucan said the power of romanias revolution was a surprise 
i didnt expect a popular explosion of such magnitude he 
said in the interview especially i didnt expect the youth in 
romania to have such a high political and civic conscience 
as he watched the rise of solidarity in poland and signs of 
democratization in other soviet bloc countries brucan said his 
main concern was to keep from being killed by ceausescu 
brucan was first put under house arrest after criticizing the 
dictators handling of riots in brasov in 1987 
in october 1988 unexpectedly he was offered a passport to go 
to the united states fearing a trap brucan said he decided to 
stop in london and moscow and make my name known so much 
internationally that the price of killing me was so high that 
ceausescu could not pay 
pressure from the united states britain and the soviet union 
saved him from arrest on his return in late november 1988 he said 
the soviets made a very reluctant promise of support if 
ceausescu fell brucan said but he described western press reports 
of a conspiracy to oust the dictator as trash 
if there was a plot and we succeeded dont you think we 
should have boasted about it and made political capital about 
it he asked it would have strengthened considerably our 
legitimacy and political modesty has no place particularly at a 
time of revolution 
the national salvation front a group of 150 intellectuals 
dissidents and workers initially pledged to stay out of the coming 
election but reneged last month 
daily protests culminated in its agreement three weeks ago to 
share power with 37 political groups in a council of national unity 
that will govern until the election 
brucan said the most difficult thing was to convince people to 
share power with the other political parties and to get across the 
point that a strong opposition is essential in a democracy 
</TEXT>
