two years ago bowman introduced its own gin which accounts for 
about 12000 cases a year 
lee is a born salesman whose accent reflects his new york roots 
his father was a columbia universityeducated doctor who practiced 
in the city 
but lee was sent to private school in virginia and in 1949 
graduated from washington amp lee university in lexington where his 
greatgrandfather served as president after the civil war 
after college he moved to the west coast and became an 
advertising executive for the san francisco chronicle twenty years 
ago he joined bowman when his brotherinlaw a smith bowman jr 
asked him to take over sales and marketing duties at the company 
founded in 1935 by bowmans father a smith bowman sr 
i basically like sales said lee whose first decision at 
bowman was to hire a public relations executive and begin traveling 
the state to give civic club speeches and newspaper and television 
interviews to promote virginia gentleman 
i went down to lynchburg one time and was on a cooking show 
he said id never cooked in my life but we did it for half an 
hour and gave away recipes it was fun 
lee who eventually succeeded the bowmans as chairman of the 
nations oldest familyowned independent bourbon distillery also 
played a role in the decision to diversify the firms products 
here we had one product bourbon he said nationally 
bourbon was not going anywhere 
bourbons share of the liquor market dwindled from 14 percent in 
1978 to 108 percent in 1988 but the trend was evident early on 
and bowman got into the vodka business in 1982 lee said 
when the companys vodka went on the market it got a boost from 
thengov charles s robb who launched his we have it made in 
virginia campaign at the same time that was pure luck lee 
said 
the companys gin came out two years ago while lee has been 
searching for new directions to take the company bowman is not 
ready to become a major national player in the liquor field he 
said 
although sales of bourbon are slumping nationally lee said 
there still are plenty of bourbon drinkers to woo away from 
competitors 
a dozen years ago bowman entered into a partnership with a 
wholesaler in florida and texas and attempted for 18 months to sell 
virginia gentleman in those two states it just didnt work 
lee said 
so having done that we realize we cant go big league like 
jim beam he said we never would have known if we hadnt 
tried 
lee keeps a small bust of gen lee in his office but most of 
the family decorations are related to his children 
he said people always want to hear stories about his 
greatgrandfather 
but we dont have any special anecdotes in the family about 
general lee he said one of the major reasons is that 
everybody got married late in life my father never knew his 
grandfather and my father was in his 50s when i was born 
we had a sense of history but we didnt have anybody sitting 
in someones lap telling about something that wasnt in dr 
freemans or bruce cattons books lee said of the pulitzer 
prizewinning biography of his greatgrandfather by douglas 
southall freeman and works by civil war historian catton thats 
just the way it was 
what lee has in mind for the tennessee offensive is a taste 
test a battle of the bourbons 
its going to be kentucky vs tennessee vs virginia he 
said 
how far is he willing to go to win 
a southern gentleman will go to any lengths to maintain the 
family honor according to a bowman brochure a virginia 
gentleman will go only to honorable lengths 
</TEXT>
