<DOCNO> AP900302-0224 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
bank of new england corp is now working under the 
official guidance of the federal government with orders to tighten 
lending practices withhold stock dividends and review the 
competence of senior managers 
federal regulators had been scrutinizing the bank for months 
because of its mountain of bad real estate loans which forced the 
company to post massive losses last year 
on thursday bank of new england announced it had signed federal 
consent orders outlining steps the bank must take to restore its 
financial health 
we regard these orders as cooperative plans we undertake in 
partnership with federal regulators said h ridgely bullock the 
banks interim chairman they all speak to running a better 
bank 
the consent orders do not include plans to cut the companys 
work force but bullock confirmed the bank expects to lay off 
thousands of workers saying we have to downsize our operation 
considerably 
under the orders bank of new england will need federal approval 
to declare stock dividends conduct financial transactions with its 
subsidiaries and pay benefits to former employees 
the bank also is required to tighten its lending practices and 
not make any commercial real estate loans without following 
prescribed guidelines 
furthermore the bank must review the performance of its senior 
managers and report any proposed changes to the government 
the banks board already has dismissed several top executives 
including former chairman walter connolly who presided over the 
banks rapid growth before its problems surfaced last year 
bullock said the bank hoped to name a permanent chairman within 
a week 
lawrence fish a former bank of boston corp executive was 
expected to be named the new chairman but bullock declined to 
confirm that 
the consent orders cover the bank holding company and its 
bostonbased subsidiary bank of new england na bullock said the 
companys four other affiliate banks which are based elsewhere in 
new england were expected to sign consent orders soon 
the boston branch also was ordered to raise its equity capital 
to 3 percent of total assets by may 31 and develop a plan to reach 
5 percent 
the bank however has told the federal comptroller of the 
currency that it does not expect to meet the may 31 deadline and 
bullock said the bank hopes to get an extension bullock said he 
expects the bank to operate under the consent order for a year or 
more 
until late last year bank of new england was the regions 
secondlargest bank behind bank of boston but the company took a 
dramatic fall as a real estate slump forced the bank to boost its 
reserves against bad loans 
bank of new england reported 1989 losses exceeding 1 billion 
and the company says it is studying whether it should have made 
larger provisions against bad loans earlier in the year 
in the meantime bank of new england has lost an estimated 5 
billion worth of deposits forcing the company to borrow money from 
the federal reserve bank of boston while it tries to sell assets to 
raise cash 
the banks borrowing is estimated above 1 billion but bullock 
said he hopes bank of new england will be out of the fed by 
april 
people look at borrowing from the fed as a trend line to 
obscurity i disagree he said instead bullock described the 
borrowing as bridge financing as the bank sells about 6 
billion worth of assets 
because of the cash crunch the bank cannot afford to pay stock 
dividends bullock said adding that he would have expected the 
bank to withhold payments regardless of the federal consent order 
i dont expect to be able to pay dividends on common stock or 
preferred stock for some time he said 
bullock said the bank still hopes to find buyers for its 
troubled loan portfolio but he added they have been harder to 
find than buyers of other assets 
