<DOCNO> AP900302-0226 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
federal commodities futures regulators have 
taken another step to blunt the congressional criticism they have 
weathered in the wake of a fraud scandal at the nations two 
largest futures exchanges 
the commodity futures trading commission which oversees the 
industry unanimously approve a change in rules governing the 
trading cards that brokers and traders use to record commodity 
futures and options transactions 
the tougher rules will make it difficult to fabricate or alter 
trading records one of the allegations made in the fraud scandals 
that rocked the two largest chicago futures exchanges last summer 
more than 40 traders at the chicago mercantile exchange and the 
chicago board of trade were indicted on charges ranging from 
racketeering to fraud for numerous alleged schemes to defraud 
customers 
during hearings for a cftc reauthorization bill last fall 
members of congress were very critical of the cftc for allowing the 
exchanges to police themselves on recording trades and other 
recordkeeping functions 
a general accounting office study of four futures exchanges last 
september found that at three of them much of the recordkeeping 
is left to the traders and brokers themselves 
the rules changes will require 
the collection of trading records within a specified schedule 
timestamping the cards 
using preprinted sequentially numbered cards that will be 
unique to each exchange member 
recording trades on both trading cards and order tickets in 
nonerasable ink 
one of the allegations in the chicago probe was that traders 
would illegally alter records to correct costly errors or change 
the time of a transaction to take advantage of a later more 
favorable price 
the new rules also would require each exchange to submit a 
written report to the commission no later than nine months after 
the effective date of the regulation detailing the systems they 
have put in place to meet the new requirements 
exchanges could seek exemption from the new rules if they can 
demonstrate members are using handheld computer terminals or other 
automated means to recrod trades and eliminate fraud 
both the bot and cme are developing handheld computer terminals 
that will replace paper trading cards but they are not expected to 
be operative in the near future 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

