<TEXT>
the departing president of exxon shipping co 
called the wreck of the exxon valdez a tragedy that never should 
have happened but said the huge alaskan oil spill did not prompt 
him to leave exxon 
frank j iarossi said thursday that although environmental 
concerns for prince william sound were justified criticism of 
exxons cleanup efforts were sometimes unwarranted 
one regret i had in that first week or so is that we didnt 
have the opportunity to really show the human side of what people 
were doing to try to bring that situation under control iarossi 
said there were people out there working for 22 hours 
in a telephone interview from his home in houston iarossi said 
he was leaving exxon to become president of the american bureau of 
shipping an international ship classification society he had been 
in charge of the shipping division since 1982 
in the first few days after the spill iarossi said press 
coverage was reasoned and really trying to understand what had 
happened but somewhere after day five or six when it hit the 
beaches there was no way to balance or bring rationale to the 
story 
news reports didnt emphasize that exxon offloaded 1 million 
barrels of oil from the exxon valdez without spilling a drop 
he said we were told by the state that the priority was to save 
five hatcheries which in fact was done 
exxon was unable to do much about the oil that had already 
spilled out of the ship and fouled shorelines though 
it was clear that we won a lot of the battle but as far as 
the public was concerned we lost the war said iarossi who was 
the first highlevel exxon official to arrive on the scene to 
coordinate cleanup after the spill 
the announcement of iarossis departure comes two days after a 
federal grand jury in anchorage indicted exxon shipping and its 
parent exxon corp on criminal felony and misdemeanor charges 
stemming from the march 24 1989 spill 
if convicted on all five counts the company could face fines 
exceeding 600 million exxon says it already has spent more than 
2 billion to clean up the effects of the nations worst oil 
disaster which spilled nearly 11 million gallons of crude into 
prince william sound 
the skipper of the valdez joseph hazelwood is on trial in 
anchorage on felony criminal mischief and misdemeanor charges that 
include operating the vessel while intoxicated if convicted he 
faces up to 7 years in prison and 61000 in fines 
les rogers a spokesman for exxon in houston said iarossis 
departure from the company was unrelated to the spill 
in answer to the question did exxon fire him no we did 
not rogers said 
iarossi said he received a whole bunch of nasty letters 
about the spill condemning him as antienvironmentalist 
i think there was a very emotional side to some of the 
reaction that didnt benefit anybody except for a venting of 
anger he said 
it certainly was a tragic incident and it never should have 
happened but i think exxon valdez became the lightning rod for a 
lot of emotion that was already there a lot of energy that was 
already there he said 
because of the spill several members of congress are proposing 
that some tankers be required to have double hulls to protect 
against oil spills 
but iarossi said doublehulls diminish tankers capacity which 
would require the building of more tankers and possibly increase 
environmental risks 
iarossi had been negotiating with the shipping bureau for 
several months and was elected by the new jerseybased group on 
feb 26 to the posts of chairman of the board and president rogers 
said iarossis last day at exxon will be march 30 
after serving in the us coast guard iarossi joined exxons 
tanker division in 1968 from 1972 to 1976 he managed a tanker 
construction program for exxon in japan he later was a marine 
advisor to exxon and became assistant manager of exxons corporate 
planning department in 1981 
