<TEXT>
federal regulators have filed a suit against the 
ernst amp young accounting firm seeking 560 million regulators say 
was lost because the auditors failed to detect illegitimate 
activities of dallasbased western savings association 
the suit filed thursday by the federal deposit insurance corp 
means the nations largest accounting firm becomes ineligible for 
most work with the fdic an agency spokesman said 
the fdic can only use ernst amp young if there is a compelling 
argument for doing so said agency spokesman alan whitney 
ernst amp young general counsel carl liggio was out of town this 
morning and unavailable to comment a woman answering the phone in 
his office said 
western savings september 1986 failure is expected to cost the 
government more than 1 billion the government continues to own 
and operate western savings which was combined with seven other 
failed texas thrifts in 1988 to form sunbelt savings of dallas 
between 1982 and 1986 western savings operated under the 
control of developer jarrett e woods jr who bought gatesville 
savings and loan association renamed it western savings and began 
making highrisk loans for construction and development 
federal regulators became interested in the thrift when they 
noted its high rate of growth and in 1984 supervisors for the 
federal home loan bank board forced western to agree to a series of 
restrictions including the hiring of a new outside auditor arthur 
young amp co 
arthur young merged with ernst amp whinney in 1989 
young performed outside audits for western savings in 1984 and 
1985 but failed to plan and conduct its audits in accordance 
with generally accepted accounting standards in numerous 
respects the fdic alleges 
the agency said arthur young failed to assess the risks of 
irregularities assigned personnel with inadequate training and 
relied unreasonably on the representations of western savings 
management 
specifically the fdic said arthur young should have reported 
bogus profits from property sales including property foreclosed by 
the thrift with many of the sales going to parties who received 
their entire financing from western savings 
it also alleged the accounting firm should have reported 
inadequate provisions for losses from loans and investments 
the suit names arthur young amp co and ernst amp young 
</TEXT>
