<TEXT>
us workers lack enthusiasm and dont enjoy 
their jobs and the best way to motivate employees may be to offer 
them more money according to most of the quality control engineers 
responding to a recent survey 
the institute of industrial engineers after examining responses 
to a survey of its members opinions on workplace productivity and 
quality issues said corporations must invest more in motivating 
employees and making the workers feel they can share in the 
companys success 
the alternative could be declining productivity and quality 
said gregory balestrero executive director of the iie based in 
norcross ga 
its affecting corporations very rapidly balestrero said 
friday from miami where he was attending a conference 
balestrero said 27 percent of the iies 40000 members responded 
to the annual survey with 752 percent of the respondents saying 
they did not think employees were enthusiastic about their jobs or 
enjoyed coming to work 
in a 1987 survey 549 percent of those responding said 
employees were enthusiastic and enjoyed coming to work 
balestrero said some major corporations notably minnesota 
mining and manufacturing co and ford motor co have instituted 
successful programs to provide employees with incentives for the 
improved performance of the company as a whole 
such gain sharing programs he said set corporate rather 
than individual goals which when exceeded provide benefits to 
everyone but relatively few corporations are making such an 
effort he said 
asked the primary motivation for employees to increase 
productivity the greatest percentage of respondents 29 percent 
listed financial reward followed by personal recognition 
increased responsibilities and pride in the job 
balestrero said in 1980 recognition topped the list but money 
began returning to prominence around 1985 
iie members include engineers and managers involved in quality 
control personnel and productivity about 68 percent of the 
members are in manufacturing businesses balestrero said 
among the other responses 
91 percent said they believe companies are more interested in 
shortterm financial gain than in longterm investment in 
productivity and quality programs 
71 percent said management does not seek employee input on 
decisions regarding things about which the employee has knowledge 
627 percent said employees are less productive than 10 years 
ago and dont work as hard 
679 percent disagreed with the statement employees take 
more pride in their work than they did 10 years ago 
851 percent disagreed with the statement employees are more 
loyal and dedicated to the company than they were 10 years ago 
586 percent disagreed that with the statement that workmanship 
is better than 10 years ago 
