<TEXT>
a federal jury on friday ordered brown amp 
williamson tobacco corp to pay 1488 million to liggett group 
inc for attempting to put liggetts generic cigarettes out of 
business through illegal pricing 
the award followed a sevenmonth antitrust trial in us 
district court on allegations that bampw illegally tried to stifle 
expansion of generic cigarette sales by its competitor in the early 
1980s 
bampw was convicted of selling generic cigarettes at below their 
cost of manufacture giving illegal discounts to undercut liggett 
sales and organizing a plan to displace liggett in the generic 
market 
brown amp williamson based in louisville ky was acquitted of 
trademark violation attorneys for durhambased liggett said they 
would seek a new trial on that issue 
the message is clear unfair competitive conduct in the 
marketplace is contrary to american law liggett president kvr 
dey said 
liggett introduced generic cigarettes in 1980 and sued bampw in 
1984 charging it tried to bring about the demise of liggetts 
lowprice brand by illegally copying liggetts trademark and trying 
to prevent expansion of generic sales the trial began last july 
bampw maintained the case should be tried in the marketplace and 
not the courts 
liggett sought 896 million in compensatory damages the amount 
the company said it lost as a result of predatory practices by bampw 
in violation of federal trade and antitrust laws 
liggett contended that it pioneered the plainlabel generic 
cigarette market in 1980 in a successful effort to carve its own 
niche at a time when sales of its regular brands were flagging 
brown amp williamson a larger tobacco company said it engaged in 
customary tactics in the highly competitive cigarette trade in 
seeking a share of the generic market 
josiah murray general counsel for the liggett group inc said 
bampw sought to bring down liggett because liggetts lowprice 
cigarettes were interfering with brown amp williamsons high profits 
on their branded cigarettes 
bampw said in statement it believed the verdict would be 
overturned because of overwhelming evidence that competition was 
not in any way injured by brown amp williamsons sale of lowpriced 
cigarettes 
liggett was owned by grand metropolitan plc when the lawsuit was 
filed it was sold to a group of private investors in 1986 and went 
public a year later 
when grandmet sold liggett an arrangement was made for liggett 
and grandmet to share equally in any proceeds of the brown amp 
williamson litigation after reimbursement of expenses 
under an agreement grandmets share in any recovery will not 
exceed 165 million plus reimbursement of all expenses relating 
to the lawsuit paid or reimbursed by grandmet or by liggett while 
it was owned by grandmet 
the balance of a recovery will be liggetts since last june 
grandmet has reimbursed liggett for 50 percent of liggetts 
expenses in connection with the case 
</TEXT>
