<TEXT>
mobil oil corp has agreed to pay 500000 in 
fines and submit to a review of its operations after it spilled 
50000 gallons of kerosene into the ground in brooklyn state 
officials said friday 
mobil also must reimburse the state for cleaning up the mess 
left when the kerosene leaked a mobil facility state department of 
environmental conservation commissioner thomas c jorling said 
in addition the company must test all product plumes under the 
facility not just the one resulting from the feb 3 spill he 
said the spill did not reach a creek that feeds into new yorks 
east river officials said 
the 500000 fine is the maximum penalty under state 
environmental conservation and navigation laws 
the state accused mobil of violating laws by failing to report 
the spill for several days and failing to test the kerosene storage 
tank before it was put back into service after reconditioning 
the 100yearold tank was reconditioned and returned to service 
jan 29 
on feb 5 mobil notified the dec that 80 gallons of kerosene 
had leaked from the tank two days earlier the company raised the 
estimated size of the release to 50000 gallons the next day the 
dec said 
mobil later claimed to have recovered 37000 gallons of kerosene 
through an underground drainage and treatment system the dec said 
mobil spokesman mark cohen said the company would work with 
state and local agencies to take whatever corrective action 
necessary to prevent such incidents from occurring in the future 
</TEXT>
