<TEXT>
texas air corp and its eastern airlines 
subsidiary threatened unspecified action friday to clear their 
names after a court report said texas air shortchanged eastern 
when it bought the airline and some of its assets 
texas air agreed earlier this week to pay eastern more than 280 
million to settle the findings by courtappointed bankruptcy 
examiner david i shapiro he concluded that texas air owes eastern 
285 million to 403 million for assets it purchased at unfairly 
low prices 
shapiros findings supported a key contention by striking 
eastern workers who claimed texas air stripped the airline of its 
most valuable assets to bolster the parents nonunion carrier 
continental airlines 
eastern and texas air said thursday they rejected the validity 
of shapiros conclusions in a statement friday they also 
threatened to take serious and considered actions to vindicate 
themselves 
we find ourselves in the intolerable position where our 
commitments to rebuild eastern are being improperly used to imply 
that texas air somehow agrees with this amateurish report and that 
our assistance to eastern somehow constitutes payment to settle any 
such liabilities the statement said 
texas air spokesman art kent declined comment on what form the 
action might take he said discussions on various options are under 
way and a decision would be made soon 
richard seltzer an attorney for the air line pilots 
association said it was difficult to see what the companies might 
do other than file an objection with federal bankruptcy court 
shapiro didnt return a telephone call seeking comment 
shapiro said in the report that he did not agree with the 
unions request that eastern be run by an outside trustee which 
was sought as protection against further asset sales by texas air 
during bankruptcy reorganization 
union attorneys insisted a trustee still should be named to take 
over management of the company 
approval of the settlement by us bankruptcy judge burton r 
lifland could remove a main obstacle in easterns effort to emerge 
from bankruptcy because some of the compensation would help 
satisfy creditor claims against the miamibased airline 
shapiro concluded for example that eastern should recover 150 
million to 250 million from texas air for the transfer of the 
system one computer reservation system and 61 million for texas 
airs acquisition of eastern in november 1986 
under the proposed settlement eastern also would receive a 25 
percent share in system one and the right to buy 40 boeing 737300 
jets at cost from sister carrier continental the settlements 
total value is estimated at more than 280 million and includes 
133 million in cash 
shapiro issued his findings following a lengthy investigation 
into the dealings between texas air eastern and continental 
undertaken as part of easterns chapter 11 bankruptcy case 
the airline sought protection from creditors five days after a 
march 4 1989 strike by machinists flight attendants and pilots 
that virtually grounded it eastern has been reorganizing as a 
smaller carrier and has hired replacements for many of the strikers 
the pilots and flight attendants unions abandoned the strike in 
november but machinists remain on strike 
 
</TEXT>
