<DOCNO> AP900302-0272 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the north american auto industry continues to 
have too much capacity and will need to shut five or six more 
plants in addition to the five closed down in recent years 
according to an independent study 
all the announced plant closings will not be enough to close 
the gap said william r pochiluk president of autofacts an 
independent consultant 
the firms study released thursday also said ford motor co 
made more efficient use of its manufacturing plant capacity last 
year than other major automakers 
in 1989 the study found a total industry capacity of 143 
million cars and light trucks down 1 percent from 1988 
overall the industry used 88 percent of its plant capacity last 
year manufacturers used 82 percent of capacity to make cars and 
101 percent of capacity for light trucks 
for the second year ford led the way with a 90 percent 
capacity utilization for cars and 107 percent for light trucks 
capacity utilization refers to how many vehicles a manufacturer 
actually produced a manufacturer producing at more than 100 
percent of capacity had to operate at overtime pochiluk said 
foreignbased producers manufactured at 94 percent of capacity 
with cars at 93 percent and light trucks at 101 percent 
chrysler corp achieved 86 percent capacity utilization overall 
reflecting below average performance of 76 percent for cars and 97 
percent for light trucks 
general motors corp recorded the lowest overall results in 1989 
an 82 percent overall capacity utilization rate with a low 76 
percent rate in cars offset by a light truck rate of 99 percent 
autofacts counts 79 automotive plants producing cars and light 
trucks in the united states and canada currently with a 
straighttime capacity of 144 million vehicles actual 1990 car 
and light truck production is scheduled to total 118 million 72 
million cars and 46 million light trucks 
five assembly plants are projected to open and five to close 
permanently by 1995 the study said but the industrys rated 
capacity will grow to 157 million units 
while domestic capacity should average 154 million units from 
1992 to 1995 production of light vehicles is projected to average 
134 million pochiluk said 
there are approximately 5 to 6 plants of excess capacity for 
the 199095 planning window the study said 
foreign manufacturers primarily japanese accepted the 
challenge to produce more in america the study said but the 
strategy backfired on domesitic automakers as exchange rates 
resulted in lower manufacturing costs for the transplant 
vehicles 
the study listed several auto plants it considered 
vulnerable for closure in the next five years including some 
where a shutdown is already pending 
they included gm plants in lakewood ga lordstown ohio 
scarborough ontario van nuys calif linden nj lansing 
mich arlington texas wentzville mo and orion mich 
also on the list was fords fox plant in dearborn mich 
chrysler plants in st louis brampton ontario and pillette road 
ontario and a gmtoyota joint venture in fremont calif 
</TEXT>
