<DOCNO> AP900302-0273 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a superior court judge friday cleared the 
way for channel one a daily news show with commercials aimed at 
teenagers to begin beaming into north carolina classrooms 
the news show being produced by whittle communications of 
knoxville tenn is set to begin nationally on monday 
after an allday hearing judge donald stephens ruled that the 
state board of education has the authority to ban the 12minute 
news program but did not follow the correct procedures in imposing 
a ban feb 1 
his order dismisses a lawsuit brought by the state board of 
education against the thomasville school system and whittle 
communications it also reverses a decision by the state board that 
contracts signed for channel one before feb 1 are void and that no 
new contracts can be signed 
after a careful review the court concludes that the state 
board of education has the authority to make rules concerning 
supplemental materials that contain advertising stephens said 
but he said the state board must follow procedures for rulemaking 
by state agencies 
the boards ban had been imposed immediately as an emergency 
rule while the board pursued procedures to make it permanent but 
stephens ruled because there was no evidence of an immediate threat 
to the public welfare by allowing channel one to proceed 
the 12minute news program contains two minutes of commercials 
and more than 2700 schools have signed up for the service 
nationwide 
about 30 school boards in north carolina have signed up for the 
service which loans local schools video equipment in exchange for 
a guarantee that the news show will be shown to students every day 
edwin speas representing the state board argued that the 
required viewing of channel one amounted to exploitation of 
students who are required to be in school under the states 
compulsory attendance law 
but stephens ruled that the contracts with whittle do not 
violate public policy or the state constitution because no valid 
rule against the contracts in effect 
we think its a victory for children and teachers in north 
carolina said max walser superintendent of the davidson county 
schools davidson countys school board which had signed a 
contract with whittle prior to the ban had filed a countersuit 
against the state board of education 
we are certainly pleased that the judge ruled as we have 
felt that the state board acted improperly said gene causby of 
the state school boards association those contracts are back in 
force 
speas said after the ruling that it did not amount to a total 
victory for channel one supporters 
the court has confirmed their the state boards authority 
in this area which was very important speas said the judge 
said that a rule can be made it just has to follow the regulations 
of the administrative procedures act 
speas said an official notice that the state board intends to 
impose the ban already has been given and a public hearing required 
by rulemaking regulations has been scheduled for april 2 
the existing contracts are valid and channel one will premiere 
in north carolina schools on march 5 said ed winter president 
of whittle communications those school systems that have not yet 
signed contracts but would like to are now free to do so 
</TEXT>
